marketingRemarks.marketingRemark: Currently under construction, this contemporary gem in the heart of Los Angeles features ivory limestone fencing, desert oak louver accents, burnished brass awnings, and a travertine and stucco facade. Nearby fine dining, shopping, The Grove, CBS Studios International, Beverly Hills, West Hollywood, Melrose and the Fairfax District allows you stay close to home. Brought to you by BRH Real Estate Development. Architecture by Zorhabian Design Group. Interiors by Ryan Saghian Interiors and Builder Brian McCabe with Engine Construction. Additional features in this modern home include a lavish basement with a HAMMAN Sauna, media den and bedroom with bath, open concept main floor, opulent second floor, epic rooftop area, convenient guest house or ADU, and a well appointed two-car garage. An ivory limestone fluted fireplace anchors the living room with white oak flooring and 20-foot pocket doors for an indoor/outdoor feel. With an open floor plan, the kitchen features integrated top tier appliances, rift oak cabinetry, and Italian porcelain countertops for added durability. A linear window adds ample light to the open kitchen which boasts a reeded oak island, stone wrapped hood, and integrated stone shelf above the range. A walnut louver feature wall with bronze pendants gives the primary bedroom a warm feel. Calcutta Viola marble paired with Cream Travertine in a checkered layout creates a unique and dramatic composition. White oak cabinetry, concrete tub, and Apparatus Studio lighting adds to the ultra-luxe look. The earthy, beige tones continue in the primary bathroom which has travertine marble walls and countertops complimented by burnished brass fixtures and enclosures. Let your imagination run wild and arrange a private session at our Beverly Hills studio to further review the materials selection and custom features to make your dreams come true.

schoolReviews.review: My children have attended this school for several years. In fact, we took them out for a few years and than came back because it is the BEST school for them. The staff and administration provides a warm, caring and nurturing environment where children can thrive.

Sending our children to Etz Jacob was one of the best choices we made all year. The transition to middle school and to a totally new environment, new kids and teachers has been a challenge. But I can't compliment the teaching and administration staff enough on their dedication to students, educational innovation and optimism. highly recommended Bitton Family
Wish I could give six stars! My son has grown so much at Perutz Etz Jacob. The teachers and staff are amazing and are committed to giving him everything he needs to succeed.
It is an ok school. Not great or anything but every child is considered equal in this school.
Good school mmkay...so yeah...it was very nice going there! so...I don't really know what else to write about...bye.

Thank G-d for Perutz Etz Jacob Hebrew Academy, a hidden gem of academic excellence infused with the best in Torah learning of any school in the state. The Rabbi, Principals, Teachers, and Administrators are all incredible and give your child personalized learning and attention styled to each individual need. I wholeheartedly recommend Perutz Etz Jacob Hebrew Academy to any family seeking the very best in Jewish education.
I am a parent of 2 kids for the last 3 year's and we are very happy, from this school it's very warm, the education is very good, English and hebrew. Highly recommended.

elementarySchools.name: Hancock Park Elementary School
elementarySchools.fullAddress: 408 S Fairfax Ave, Los Angeles, CA 90036

schoolReviews.review: My child was in SDC classroom few years back. I am writing this review because after moving I realized it was worst ever school and not able to get over. Money minded school, asking for compulsory donation and keep sending papers until you start giving minimum 86$ per month. No public schools asking this way in entire California. Administration is worst too.

The school has opportunities for all kids to be challenged. The donation amount doubled during the pandemic and yet programs that do not include Music classes for all kids. I am giving 3 stars to raise awareness that if the school requires us to give close to 1K Music classes should be inclusive of every grade.

My daughter is in the 3rd grade at ---- Park School and we could not be happier. The teachers at this school are incredibly invested in the well-being and education of every child that enters their doors. There has been a move to more social-emotional learning as well as mindfulness which has definitely been helpful with the current remote schooling situation. The booster club is excellent at fundraising, giving our children access to computer lab, visual art, dance, music, extra teaching aides, PE, chess, math enrichment and even African dance! All the things every school should have but can't due to lack of state funding. It is also an exceptionally diverse school, with families not just LA but from around the world. While our teachers have handled the jump to remote learning quite well considering, we are definitely looking forward to the day when we can send our daughter back in person, she misses school so much!

I have 2 children at the school, a 2nd grader and a 4th grader. They both love school and have since kindergarten. The school staff have always made my children and our family feel welcome and involved. The teachers work exceptionally hard and make the learning engaging, relevant and fun. We love all the programs the school has to offer- PE, Computer Lab, Dance, Visual Art, Orchestra, Music, and Science Lab. My children miss being at HPS and they hope to go back soon when everything is safe.

My son had a wonderful education at ---- Park Elementary. He received a lot of enrichment due to the outstanding parent engagement. He especially enjoyed his science lab time, computer lab, visual arts, dance, robotics, and chess classes. His teachers were caring and his peers were from all over the world. There is a strong emphasis on kindness and socio-emotional development as well.

School is more focused on gathering donations which surely is helpful, but Principal should focus on quality education as well, parent feedback is heard when raised but nothing happens thereafter. School should recognize good teachers and help them to advance their careers, they should also recognize teachers who lack passion to teach.Rating of this school is falling and is visible due to lack of attention to education. Suggestion to teachers and Principal, please recognize student education needs and abilities, please motivate, incite and be creative to help students excel, challenge their abilities.

Review for Kindergarten My child absolutely LOVES going to school. Her teacher has a fun approach to teaching which keeps the students engaged and helps students retain the information given. I have noticed a great difference in my child's education. There was a bullying situation in my child's classroom that was quickly put to an end. This school has a zero tolerance for bullying. I love the school community and events that are held to raise funds for the school. The staff is friendly and welcoming. Looking forward to the other grades.

elementarySchools.name: Rosewood Avenue Elementary School, School For Advanced Studies
elementarySchools.fullAddress: 503 N Croft Ave, West Hollywood, CA 90048

schoolReviews.review: My daughter did 3rd grade through 5th grade at Rosewood. She was in a private school before switching her over to Rosewood. Rosewood is her all time best school. She is now in the 8th grade and cannot stop raving about how wonderful her experience at Rosewood was. Her teachers were all wonderful. The Principal Mrs. Crowder was great and showed she cared about every child at the school. My daughter was in the adopt the arts program with Ms. Molly and sang with Foreigner and Moby. She was also in the after school program and performed with their dance group. Rosewood is a great public school. Many good memories. Excellent teachers and staff. I only have one child, but if I had more they would definitely attend Rosewood!

I completely disagree with the comment on the school and its Special Needs program My son is Special Needs and is in his fourth year at Rosewood. The teachers, Principal and especially the students are wonderful with him. He loves the school. I do wish the District provided more resources but that isn't within the control of anyone at Rosewood.
I plan on removing my child from this school due to the lack of resources available for children of special needs, learning disabilities, etc.

Rosewood is a true gem of a school. The principal and teachers strive for both academic excellence and strong socio-emotional development for all students, from high achievers to those needing extra help. The school just became a stem magnet focusing on urban planning and urban design, and the teachers all worked very hard to deign--and are very excited to implement--the new stem magnet curriculum. The teachers, as well as the principal, Mrs. Crowder, are committed to professional development and to implementing the latest techniques (for example, Mrs. Crowder just secured a grant for wobble desks/seats for students who have trouble sitting still for too long, and will also be implementing yoga/meditation for the kids). The teachers are all caring, energetic, motivated, and devoted to the students. Principal Crowder not only knows the name of every student in her school, but knows how they're doing in school, what's going on with them at home, and what they need from the school. The kids are exceedingly nice--several students came to Rosewood to get away from bullying at their prior schools, and have not experienced anything like that at Rosewood. The school is very diverse, including socio-economically (which makes its test scores very impressive, since generally, the richer the families at the school, the higher the test scores). There is an impressive array of extra-curriculars at the school: a steller music program provided by the non-profit Adopt the Arts (including an honors choir), a garden program taught by a master gardener, dance/theater/visual arts, a science lab, a computer center, a full library with an amazing librarian, after-school musicals (for a fee), and free after-school programs until 6pm. This is our fifth year at the school, and we've been extremely happy. My son loves his teachers, has great friends, enjoys going to school, is learning a lot and doing very well.

The office staff is outstanding as well as the teachers and Principal Crowder is so caring and helpful. I love this school so much! They are really doing an outstanding job surpassing all expectations and putting to bed any anxiety you may have as a parent leaving your little one.

I love Rosewood! From Mrs. Laura and Mrs. Teresa at the front desk, Mrs. Tina in the cafeteria or Mrs. Rosa in the nursing office, everyone here is fantastic! Principal Crowder is truly a gem! She greets the students every morning one by one always by name and with a smile. My daughter is in Kinder and her teacher is Mrs. Neil. My daughter is excited every day to go to school. I love everything about Rosewood. We are so blessed to be part of the Huskies family.

Principal Crowder is outstanding,She knows each kid by name, and knows the parents too. The office staff is excellent, my daughter's teacher is ms campos she is an amazing person my daughter love her we are really happy in this school

schoolReviews.review: Excellent. I would assume that the previous negative comments are from parents that have been difficult and unwilling to artner with the school to find solutions. I (and the many other families) are thrilled with the Academy.
They are not devoted to their job and are very lazy. They don't want to teach you they want they want to take your money and favor other kids!
Very irresponsible, needs lots of improvement!!! The principle is also very childish. The teachers don't give enough disciplinary action.

Maimonides Early Childhood Education has deteriorated rapidly over the last 3 years. Once a top rate program, it is now being run by unqualified and inexperienced educators for the most part, and great, experienced teachers have been replaced by young and inexperienced teachers who are not of the same caliber. The program has suffered significantly and many parents who were once thrilled with the program have taken their children elsewhere.

N/A
Although we hope that a new building for girls will be forthcoming, Rabbi Steinberg's involvement as consultant and Rabbi Emeritus is more than worthwhile. The info needs to be updated as well.

My child is attending in this school and participating in leadership group. In this school year, all good teachers in SAS/Regular programs left due to conflict with new principal and the leadership group is not what it used to be. The teacher who is in charge of leadership group routinely yells to students without respect and a proper reason and everyday my child gets stressed because of it. Leadership group is no longer help for college application. Finally my child graduates soon. If your child will attend in this school, please consider it unless your child attends in Magnet program.
My first year at this school was amazing, it's not like what I think a typical High School would be. The teachers and staff are supportive and every day there is something new to learn about.

After working at a number of schools I feel Fairfax High School is a great school. The energy of the entire campus is positive and feels quite normal. Every LAUSD school has the same issues with limited services, bad food, and a typical 36:1 student-teacher ratio. The majority of the kids are bused in, but I feel we get the cream of the crop. The school has a rich history of servicing kids who want to be here. Many of the students care about graduation and do well overall. As mentioned earlier I came from schools where students came in with an impoverish mindset. I don't feel that to be the case here. The campus is very diverse and representative of the real world. My child has been sheltered attending a certified Montessori school where she is not tested as much as LAUSD schools. Eventually, she will need to experience the "general population" and I believe Fairfax High School would be a nice transition.

Disappointed is not saying enough. There is no clear contact method or interaction beteen the teachers, counselors, and principal. There are more new staff members that don't seem to know how things work at this school than I care for, especially the principal and counselor. The teachers want your children to turn in the work but there is no clear way for parents to assist to make sure this is getting done. These are still children. As I was told by the prinicipal, teachers are not encouraged or required to post HW, CW, projects, etc. on-line. How do they expect parent participation. All parents can't take off work to be at the school. Teachers should learn to utilize the tools given to them to advocate parent participation (i.e. computers and e-mails). Come on now, if teachers and other public school staff do not want to foster a circle of success for students, please find another career.

I currently attend Fairfax, and overall, it's a pretty good school. I'm in the Schools for Advanced Studies, and the teachers for this program are generally good. I would have to say some of the best teachers are the AP teachers, but not all are great. There are teachers who hardly teach at all, and it's all up to you to learn, but it all depends on how driven the students are. The school is extremely diverse and offers a pretty good quantity of extra curriculars. The students at Fairfax are generally open minded. The budget cuts the school has suffered haven't allowed it to improve a whole lot, but the campus has become significantly nicer. The school allows for educational and social expansion.

I have been going to Fairfax for only 8 months and I'm in love with it.... the students are super friendly and teachers are committed to their jobs... they teach us a looott more than what the textbook says.... and AP teachers are the best there could be.... The budget cuts are causing some problems but the entire school staff and student bodies are working to make things better.. Fairfax is awesome... GO LIONS!!

Currently, i'm a student at Fairfax High, and i have to say that we have THE best AP teachers who are dedicated and willing to help students on their path to success. There are tons of rumors out there that Fairfax is a "bad school", but we are actually sending students to ivy leagues and our school is improving each year! I love the culture and people here at Fairfax coming from a suburban area. I love the School of Advanced Studies program and I know that Fairfax is helping me in every way to succeed in college and beyond. Go lions!!

schoolReviews.review: My child is attending in this school and participating in leadership group. In this school year, all good teachers in SAS/Regular programs left due to conflict with new principal and the leadership group is not what it used to be. The teacher who is in charge of leadership group routinely yells to students without respect and a proper reason and everyday my child gets stressed because of it. Leadership group is no longer help for college application. Finally my child graduates soon. If your child will attend in this school, please consider it unless your child attends in Magnet program.
My first year at this school was amazing, it's not like what I think a typical High School would be. The teachers and staff are supportive and every day there is something new to learn about.

After working at a number of schools I feel Fairfax High School is a great school. The energy of the entire campus is positive and feels quite normal. Every LAUSD school has the same issues with limited services, bad food, and a typical 36:1 student-teacher ratio. The majority of the kids are bused in, but I feel we get the cream of the crop. The school has a rich history of servicing kids who want to be here. Many of the students care about graduation and do well overall. As mentioned earlier I came from schools where students came in with an impoverish mindset. I don't feel that to be the case here. The campus is very diverse and representative of the real world. My child has been sheltered attending a certified Montessori school where she is not tested as much as LAUSD schools. Eventually, she will need to experience the "general population" and I believe Fairfax High School would be a nice transition.

Disappointed is not saying enough. There is no clear contact method or interaction beteen the teachers, counselors, and principal. There are more new staff members that don't seem to know how things work at this school than I care for, especially the principal and counselor. The teachers want your children to turn in the work but there is no clear way for parents to assist to make sure this is getting done. These are still children. As I was told by the prinicipal, teachers are not encouraged or required to post HW, CW, projects, etc. on-line. How do they expect parent participation. All parents can't take off work to be at the school. Teachers should learn to utilize the tools given to them to advocate parent participation (i.e. computers and e-mails). Come on now, if teachers and other public school staff do not want to foster a circle of success for students, please find another career.

I currently attend Fairfax, and overall, it's a pretty good school. I'm in the Schools for Advanced Studies, and the teachers for this program are generally good. I would have to say some of the best teachers are the AP teachers, but not all are great. There are teachers who hardly teach at all, and it's all up to you to learn, but it all depends on how driven the students are. The school is extremely diverse and offers a pretty good quantity of extra curriculars. The students at Fairfax are generally open minded. The budget cuts the school has suffered haven't allowed it to improve a whole lot, but the campus has become significantly nicer. The school allows for educational and social expansion.

I have been going to Fairfax for only 8 months and I'm in love with it.... the students are super friendly and teachers are committed to their jobs... they teach us a looott more than what the textbook says.... and AP teachers are the best there could be.... The budget cuts are causing some problems but the entire school staff and student bodies are working to make things better.. Fairfax is awesome... GO LIONS!!

Currently, i'm a student at Fairfax High, and i have to say that we have THE best AP teachers who are dedicated and willing to help students on their path to success. There are tons of rumors out there that Fairfax is a "bad school", but we are actually sending students to ivy leagues and our school is improving each year! I love the culture and people here at Fairfax coming from a suburban area. I love the School of Advanced Studies program and I know that Fairfax is helping me in every way to succeed in college and beyond. Go lions!!

schoolReviews.review: My child loves her school. It’s a happy and fun environment. One of the reasons decided to move was that the schools in the area are magnet. 7th st elem will be an all magnet school starting next year. It’s great to know that all her classmates will be on the same page. They are also currently making renovations and we are excited to see the end result.
The only Arts Magnet Elementary school in LAUSD.Great location with port view.New principal Wells transforming school.Great supportive community.Excellent choice for kids with an Arts focus.
I am completely satisfied with my son's experience at this school so far.

This use to be a great school until the principal who use to be a teacher took over! Now the school has taken a turn for the worse with staff and parents being very displeased! She seems to make up her own rules, is unfair when it comes to discipline and pretty much does not have a clue on how to run a school! Schools are supposed to be all about the kids but in her case it's almost like she has her own personal agenda to benefit her and a certain few that buddy up to her! I can honestly say I am no longer happy with this school and if she continues to be principal my kids will no longer attend!

The principal unfortunately is the worst thing to ever happen to this school! On top of failing the students by not providing a safe campus (my child has been beaten up, and even threatened with bodily harm) she is cold and unwelcoming! She will not take the time to meet with parents about the crumbled PTO, and about the fact that this school has dismantled of all the arts.. (I.E. There is no art to grow on, music, choir, or drama)! Do not send your child here! Especially if they are gifted! The only plus side to this school is some amazing teachers.. Some! And I feel bad that they are forced into a corner with this woman as their leader! Where is the old principal?! This school needs a real one!

Hey, has anyone noticed lately a few familiar faces missing?? A beloved 5th grade teacher? Our #1 parent volunteer? A favorite substitute? Hmmmm?! Wonder what's happened to them? They have all been run outa school by our principals inability to be a leader. The only thing that is holding this school together is our AMAZING teachers. Someone mentioned bringing back our last principal, Mrs Saldivar? I wish!!! Our little school with a big heart is turning out to be a BIG mess. And who is to blame? Our principal. When you don't support those who have always supported you, you are going to have problems. Respect is earned.

I am wondering why my review just magically disappeared from the web site after a couple of days I posted it? Isn't this website partial and safe for all parents and teachers to express their point of view? What happened here? Just wondering...LAUSD receives a bomb threat and they cancel classes for that day. I received a phone call from Dodson notifying me first thing in the morning. From seventh street...nada! How much does it take to make and send a robocall to all the parents, even when we would have to hear the principal talking to us like if we were little kids? I heard from a friend that classes were cancelled but lots of parents drove to school only to find out there. What was the principal doing or thinking? What if our kids were in real danger? I guess it is the same as when there was a sewer leak at school and she didn't even bothered to notify us while the kids kept playing and walking all over it and smelling that stench. I guess the fact of getting a teacher that is not prepared really to be a principal shows in every aspect of the school, even when seeing how low scores had gone down since she took over...can we get Lisa Saldivar back? For her the kids were her #1 priority at all times!

schoolReviews.review: hi this school did a lot for me when i first started i know i was really bad. but with the help of my teachers and my lovely principal. i did it know i have my own business witch is a dog grooming salon and i am back to school.know i am studding vet tech and i planing to do more in my life.
Small comfortable school that let you work at your own pace.

San Antonio High school was the best choice i ever made after making bad decisions in my former high school. Thanks to the helpful staff and teachers i was able to become responsible and independent for myself and studies, which I'm eternally thankful for since it made my college life more easy. The teachers also provide great tutoring for any subject and have a great sense of humor with the students. I'm a proud 2013 graduate from this great high school and a successful college student. I just highly advise to please over look the SAT's and have your son/daughter speak with staff and helpful teachers about it in S.A.H.S. as soon as possible. If no interest is shown, the S.A.T's won't be provided for him/her if it's to late to register for the test. I know this from my past experience.

Concerned for my son education, I looked for the best available HS in the area. I found out that SAHS had made the API for 4 years and the AYP for three years in a row. SAHS is also accredited by the Western Association of School and Colleges. The school recieved an unheard 6-year accreditation by WASC. This speaks volumes about the school. Their academic program is student centered and the atmosphere is simply the best you can find in any school. I highly recommend this school for your children. By the way, SAHS is the only school that has made the API & AYP in LAUSD Local District 6.

As a concerned parent, I can honestly say that SAHS is one of the best schools in LAUSD. The caring atmosphere is unique; this is a student center school whose results are superior to other schools in the area.
this school was amazing when i attended, only reason i graduated! the staff is very supportive of the students.

schoolReviews.review: My child is attending in this school and participating in leadership group. In this school year, all good teachers in SAS/Regular programs left due to conflict with new principal and the leadership group is not what it used to be. The teacher who is in charge of leadership group routinely yells to students without respect and a proper reason and everyday my child gets stressed because of it. Leadership group is no longer help for college application. Finally my child graduates soon. If your child will attend in this school, please consider it unless your child attends in Magnet program.
My first year at this school was amazing, it's not like what I think a typical High School would be. The teachers and staff are supportive and every day there is something new to learn about.

After working at a number of schools I feel Fairfax High School is a great school. The energy of the entire campus is positive and feels quite normal. Every LAUSD school has the same issues with limited services, bad food, and a typical 36:1 student-teacher ratio. The majority of the kids are bused in, but I feel we get the cream of the crop. The school has a rich history of servicing kids who want to be here. Many of the students care about graduation and do well overall. As mentioned earlier I came from schools where students came in with an impoverish mindset. I don't feel that to be the case here. The campus is very diverse and representative of the real world. My child has been sheltered attending a certified Montessori school where she is not tested as much as LAUSD schools. Eventually, she will need to experience the "general population" and I believe Fairfax High School would be a nice transition.

Disappointed is not saying enough. There is no clear contact method or interaction beteen the teachers, counselors, and principal. There are more new staff members that don't seem to know how things work at this school than I care for, especially the principal and counselor. The teachers want your children to turn in the work but there is no clear way for parents to assist to make sure this is getting done. These are still children. As I was told by the prinicipal, teachers are not encouraged or required to post HW, CW, projects, etc. on-line. How do they expect parent participation. All parents can't take off work to be at the school. Teachers should learn to utilize the tools given to them to advocate parent participation (i.e. computers and e-mails). Come on now, if teachers and other public school staff do not want to foster a circle of success for students, please find another career.

I currently attend Fairfax, and overall, it's a pretty good school. I'm in the Schools for Advanced Studies, and the teachers for this program are generally good. I would have to say some of the best teachers are the AP teachers, but not all are great. There are teachers who hardly teach at all, and it's all up to you to learn, but it all depends on how driven the students are. The school is extremely diverse and offers a pretty good quantity of extra curriculars. The students at Fairfax are generally open minded. The budget cuts the school has suffered haven't allowed it to improve a whole lot, but the campus has become significantly nicer. The school allows for educational and social expansion.

I have been going to Fairfax for only 8 months and I'm in love with it.... the students are super friendly and teachers are committed to their jobs... they teach us a looott more than what the textbook says.... and AP teachers are the best there could be.... The budget cuts are causing some problems but the entire school staff and student bodies are working to make things better.. Fairfax is awesome... GO LIONS!!

Currently, i'm a student at Fairfax High, and i have to say that we have THE best AP teachers who are dedicated and willing to help students on their path to success. There are tons of rumors out there that Fairfax is a "bad school", but we are actually sending students to ivy leagues and our school is improving each year! I love the culture and people here at Fairfax coming from a suburban area. I love the School of Advanced Studies program and I know that Fairfax is helping me in every way to succeed in college and beyond. Go lions!!
